# PurePage — Privacy Policy

**Last updated: April 2026**

## Overview

PurePage is a Chrome extension that strips any web page down to a clean, distraction-free reading view. This policy explains how the extension handles your data.

## Data collection

PurePage does **not** collect, store, transmit or share any personal data with third parties.

## How it works

- When you click Open reader view, PurePage extracts the article content from the current tab using Mozilla's open source Readability.js library
- The extracted content is stored temporarily in `chrome.storage.local` on your device only, to pass it to the reader view tab
- Your reading preferences (theme, font, font size, CE highlights) are saved locally in `chrome.storage.local` and never leave your device
- No page content or personal data is ever sent to any external server

## Permissions

| Permission | Reason |
|---|---|
| `activeTab` | To access the current tab's content for extraction |
| `scripting` | To inject the Readability.js extraction script into the active page |
| `storage` | To save your reading preferences and pass article content to the reader view |

## Third party libraries

PurePage bundles the following open source libraries, which run entirely in your browser:

- **Readability.js** (Mozilla) — extracts article content from web pages
- **OpenDyslexic** font — an optional reading font designed to improve readability for people with dyslexia

Neither library transmits any data externally.

